401. This story points to a tradition which is one among many indications that in old days the Tiber water was much higher than in recent times, and much of the ground about, that in historic times was dry, was once lake or swamp. Thus the valley between the Palatine and Aventine (Circus Maximus 405), the valley between the Palatine and Capitol (Velabrum 405), the lacus Curtius in the forum, (403), the marsh in the Campus Martius (Palus Caprea), are all probablybold swamps fed by Tiber water. The myths of Vertumnus who turned back the flood (410), and Romulus and Remus being floated ashore on the Palatine slope, are other signs of the same thing. (Burri, p. 21, 599.)
